  "text": "where d(n) is the observed data, y(n) is the output of the network and N s the number of samples. Finally, the ANOVA Friedman's test was used to check whether the approaches actually provided different results [CITATION_1] . The p-values achieved were: 6.52336e-009, for the period 1952/1956; 2.88366e-007 for 1972/1986; and 0.0975 to 1981/1985 . This indicates that the prediction performances are, indeed, different or, in other words, that the prediction method directly affects the overall results.",
